I believe there have been some fairly long threads on this subject in .misc
that went along the lines of...

If your HD controller is ISA, it only has 24 address lines, and can thus only
access the first 16Mb of memory. In this case OS/2 uses the memory above 16mb
as a fast swap file. Other bus types have 32 address lines so can address 4
Gigs directly, if this limitation is causing you problems with your
PCI/VLB/EISA bus card, then mail me and I'll take a couple of gigs off you :)

Having a look in the system information tool should tell you about your
controller's memory addressing abilities, and how much of your ram is system
memory and how much swapfile.

